The '''UCI Hall of Fame''' was launched by the ''[[Union Cycliste Internationale]]'' (UCI) in 2002 to "honor all those who by their heroic deeds or their personalities have greatly contributed to the glory and development of cycling sport throughout the world".<ref name="uci-press">{{cite news|authorlink1=https://web.archive.org/web/20171110001656/http://oldsite.uci.ch/francais/news/news_2002/20020413_comm.htm|title=Les 100 ans de Paris-Roubaix et l'inuaguration CMC de l'UCI a Aigle|trans-title=|url=http://oldsite.uci.ch/francais/news/news_2002/20020413_comm.htm|accessdate=10 November 2017|publisher=[[Union Cycliste Internationale]]|date=14 April 2002|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171110001656/http://oldsite.uci.ch/francais/news/news_2002/20020413_comm.htm|archivedate=10 November 2017|language=French}}</ref> The inauguration was part of the celebrations marking the 100th anniversary of both the [[Paris–Roubaix]] race and the founding of the UCI, which also included the opening of the [[World Cycling Centre]] in Aigle, Switzerland,<ref name="uci-press" /> where the hall of fame is located.<ref>{{cite web|authorlink1=10 November 2017|title=Guided visit|url=http://www.uci.ch/mm/Document/News/wccSeminars/16/57/82/2017_CMC-fiches-VisiteGuidee-UK_English.pdf|publisher=[[Union Cycliste Internationale]]|accessdate=10 November 2017|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171110004010/http://www.uci.ch/mm/Document/News/wccSeminars/16/57/82/2017_CMC-fiches-VisiteGuidee-UK_English.pdf|archive-date=10 November 2017}}</ref> There have been no inductions since 2002.

